    "body": "This PR changes a few things in the inlay_hint and diagnostic LSP code.\r\n\r\n1. It re-introduces the `enabled` flag for the buffer state tables. Previously I was relying on the presence of an autocmd id in the state table to track whether inlay_hint / diagnostic was enabled for a buffer. There are two reasons why this doesn't work well:\r\n  a. Each time inlay_hint / diagnostic is enabled, we call `nvim_buf_attach` on the buffer, resulting in multiple `on_reload` or `on_detach` callbacks being registered.\r\n  b. Commands like `bwipeout` delete buffer local autocmds, sometimes before our `on_detach` callbacks have a chance to delete them first. This causes the error referenced in #24456.\r\n2. Change the `LspDetach` autocmd to run each time (i.e., I removed the `once` flag from it). Since we're only registering autocmds once per buffer now, we need to make sure that we set the enabled flag properly each time the LSP client detaches from the buffer.\r\n3. Have the `LspNotify` handler also refresh the inlay_hint / diagnostics when receiving the `textDocument/didOpen` event. Before this point, the LSP backend doesn't have the contents of the buffer, and so can't provide inlay hints or diagnostics.\r\n\r\n\r\nDownsides of this approach:\r\n* When inlay_hint / diagnostics are disabled on a buffer, it will continue to receive `LspNotify` events for that buffer. The callback exits early since the `enabled` flag is false.\r\n\r\nAlternatives:\r\n* Can we wrap the call to `nvim_del_autocmd` in `pcall` to swallow any errors resulting from trying to delete the autocmd?\r\n\r\nFixes #24456\r\n\r\n",
    "closed_at": "2023-08-01T12:13:52Z",
